# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ablative-case
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ablative-case/abessive-case] In linguistics, **abessive** (abbreviated **abe** or **abess**), **caritive** (abbreviated **car**) and **privative** (abbreviated **priv**) is the grammatical case expressing the lack or absence of the marked noun.
[src:ablative-case/abessive-case] The name *abessive* is derived from *abesse* "to be away/absent", and is especially used in reference to Uralic languages.
[src:ablative-case/abessive-case] The name *caritive* is derived from Latin: *carere* "to lack", and is especially used in reference to Caucasian languages.
[src:ablative-case/abessive-case] The name *privative* is derived from Latin: *privare* "to deprive".
[src:ablative-case/abessive-case] In the Somali language, the abessive case is marked by *-la'*.
[src:ablative-case/abessive-case] In Martuthunira, the privative case is formed with either *-wirriwa* or *-wirraa*.
[src:ablative-case/abessive-case] In the Finnish language, the abessive case is marked by *-tta* for back vowels and *-ttä* for front vowels according to vowel harmony.
[src:ablative-case/abessive-case] There is debate as to whether this is interference from Estonian.
[src:ablative-case/abessive-case] Unlike in Finnish, the abessive is commonly used in both written and spoken Estonian.
[src:ablative-case/abessive-case] Tallinn has a pair of bars that play on the use of the comitative and abessive, the *Nimeta baar* (the nameless bar) and the *Nimega baar* (the bar with a name).
[src:ablative-case/abessive-case] Son vuõʹlji domoi mainsteǩâni mõʹnt leäi puättam.
[src:ablative-case/abessive-case] Unlike Finnish, the Skolt Sámi abessive has no competing expression for lack of an item.
[src:ablative-case/abessive-case] The abessive marker for nouns in Inari Sámi is *-táá*.
[src:ablative-case/abessive-case] The corresponding non-finite verb form is *-hánnáá*, *-hinnáá* or *-hennáá*.
[src:ablative-case/abessive-case] The abessive is not used productively in the Western Sámi languages, although it may occur as a cranberry morpheme.
[src:ablative-case/abessive-case] In Erzya-Mordvin, the abessive case suffix is *-(v)ťeme* or *-(v)tomo*, e.g.
[src:ablative-case/abessive-case] *pevťeme* "endless", *kudovtomo* "homeless" etc.
[src:ablative-case/abessive-case] In Hungarian, the abessive case is marked by *-talan* for back vowels and *-telen* for front vowels according to vowel harmony.
[src:ablative-case/abessive-case] Sometimes, with certain roots, the suffix becomes *-tlan* or *-tlen*.
[src:ablative-case/abessive-case] There is also the postposition *nélkül*, which also means without, but is not meant for physical locations.
[src:ablative-case/abessive-case] Eljöttél Magyarországra a testvéred nélkül?
[src:ablative-case/abessive-case] In Mongolian, the privative suffix is -гүй (*-güy*).
[src:ablative-case/abessive-case] It is not universally considered to be a case, because the suffix does not conform to vowel harmony or undergo any stem-dependent orthographical variation.
[src:ablative-case/abessive-case] However, its grammatical function is the precise inverse of the comitative case, and the two form a pair of complementary case forms.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] In artificial intelligence (AI), especially machine learning, ablation is the removal of a component of an AI system.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] The term is by analogy with biology: removal of components of an organism.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] Genetic ablation is another term for gene silencing, in which gene expression is abolished through the alteration or deletion of genetic sequence information.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] In cell ablation, individual cells in a population or culture are destroyed or removed.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] Both can be used as experimental tools, as in loss-of-function experiments.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] In medicine, ablation is the removal of a part of biological tissue, usually by surgery.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] Surface ablation of the skin (dermabrasion, also called resurfacing because it induces regeneration) can be carried out by chemicals (chemoablation), by lasers (laser ablation), by freezing (cryoablation), or by electricity (fulguration).
[src:ablative-case/ablation] Its purpose is to remove skin spots, aged skin, wrinkles, thus rejuvenating it.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] Surface ablation is also employed in otolaryngology for several kinds of surgery, such as the one for snoring.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] The term is also often used in the context of laser ablation, a process in which a laser breaks a material's molecular bonds.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] For a laser to ablate tissues, the power density or fluence must be high, otherwise thermocoagulation occurs, which is simply thermal vaporization of the tissues.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] In cardiology, Radiofrequency ablation (RFA) can be used to treat a variety of cardiac arrhythmia such as supraventricular tachycardia, Wolff–Parkinson–White syndrome (WPW), ventricular tachycardia, and more recently as management of atrial fibrillation.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] Rotablation is a type of arterial cleansing that consists of inserting a tiny, diamond-tipped, drill-like device into the affected artery to remove fatty deposits or plaque.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] The procedure is used in the treatment of coronary heart disease to restore blood flow.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] Microwave ablation (MWA) is similar to RFA but at higher frequencies of electromagnetic radiation.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] High-intensity focused ultrasound (HIFU) ablation removes tissue from within the body noninvasively.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] Bone marrow ablation is a process whereby the human bone marrow cells are eliminated in preparation for a bone marrow transplant.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] This is performed using high-intensity chemotherapy and total body irradiation.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] As such, it has nothing to do with the vaporization techniques described in the rest of this article.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] Ablation of brain tissue is used for treating certain neurological disorders, particularly Parkinson's disease, and sometimes for psychiatric disorders as well.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] Recently, some researchers reported successful results with genetic ablation.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] In particular, genetic ablation is potentially a much more efficient method of removing unwanted cells, such as tumor cells, because large numbers of animals lacking specific cells could be generated.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] Genetically ablated lines can be maintained for a prolonged period of time and shared within the research community.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] Researchers at Columbia University report of reconstituted caspases combined from *C. elegans* and humans, which maintain a high degree of target specificity.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] The genetic ablation techniques described could prove useful in battling cancer.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] Electro-ablation breaks through highly resistive oxide surfaces, such as those found on titanium and other exotic metals and alloys without melting the underlying non-oxidised metal or alloy.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] The process is capable of providing surface finishing for a wide range of exotic and widely used metals and alloys, including: titanium, stainless steel, niobium, chromium–cobalt, Inconel, aluminium, and a range of widely available steels and alloys.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] Electro-ablation is very effective at achieving high levels of surface finishing in holes, valleys and hidden or internal surfaces on metallic workpieces (parts).
[src:ablative-case/ablation] The process is particularly applicable to components produced by additive manufacturing process, such as 3D-printed metals.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] These components tend to be produced with roughness levels well above 5–20 micron.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] Electro-ablation can be used to quickly reduce the surface roughness to less than 0.8 micron, allowing the post-process to be used for volume production surface finishing.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] In glaciology and meteorology, ablation—the opposite of accumulation—refers to all processes that remove snow, ice, or water from a glacier or snowfield.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] Ablation refers to the melting of snow or ice that runs off the glacier, evaporation, sublimation, calving, or erosive removal of snow by wind.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] Air temperature is typically the dominant control of ablation, with precipitation exercising secondary control.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] In a temperate climate during ablation season, ablation rates typically average around 2 mm/h.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] Where solar radiation is the dominant cause of snow ablation (e.g., if air temperatures are low under clear skies), characteristic ablation textures such as suncups and penitentes may develop on the snow surface.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] Ablation can refer to mass loss from the upper surface of a glacier or ocean-driven melt and calving on the face of a glacier terminus.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] Ablation can refer either to the processes removing ice and snow or to the quantity of ice and snow removed.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] Debris-covered glaciers have also been shown to greatly impact the ablation process.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] There is a thin debris layer that can be located on the top of glaciers that intensifies the ablation process below the ice.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] The debris-covered parts of a glacier that is experiencing ablation are sectioned into three categories which include ice cliffs, ponds, and debris.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] These three sections allow scientists to measure the heat digested by the debris-covered area and is calculated.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] The calculations are dependent on the area and net absorbed heat amounts in regards to the entire debris-covered zones.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] These types of calculations are done to various glaciers to understand and analyze future patterns of melting.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] Moraine (glacial debris) is moved by natural processes that allow for down-slope movement of materials on the glacier body.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] It is noted that if the slope of a glacier is too high then the debris will continue to move along the glacier to a further location.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] The sizes and locations of glaciers vary around the world, so depending on the climate and physical geography the varieties of debris can differ.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] The size and magnitude of the debris is dependent on the area of glacier and can vary from dust-size fragments to blocks as large as a house.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] There have been many experiments done to demonstrate the effect of debris on the surface of glaciers.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] Yoshiyuki Fujii, a professor at the National Institute of Polar Research, designed an experiment that showed ablation rate was accelerated under a thin debris layer and was retarded under a thick one as compared with that of a natural snow surface.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] This science is significant due to the importance of long-term availability of water resources and assess glacier response to climate change.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] Natural resource availability is a major drive behind research conducted in regards to the ablation process and overall study of glaciers.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] Laser ablation is greatly affected by the nature of the material and its ability to absorb energy, therefore the wavelength of the ablation laser should have a minimum absorption depth.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] Surface ablation of the cornea for several types of eye refractive surgery is now common, using an excimer laser system (LASIK and LASEK).
[src:ablative-case/ablation] Since the cornea does not grow back, laser is used to remodel the cornea refractive properties to correct refraction errors, such as astigmatism, myopia, and hyperopia.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] Laser ablation is also used to remove part of the uterine wall in women with menstruation and adenomyosis problems in a process called endometrial ablation.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] Researchers have demonstrated a successful technique for ablating subsurface tumors with minimal thermal damage to surrounding healthy tissue, by using a focused laser beam from an ultra-short pulse diode laser source.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] Antifouling paints and other related coatings are routinely used to prevent the buildup of microorganisms and other animals, such as barnacles for the bottom hull surfaces of recreational, commercial and military sea vessels.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] Ablative paints are often utilized for this purpose to prevent the dilution or deactivation of the antifouling agent.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] Over time, the paint will slowly decompose in the water, exposing fresh antifouling compounds on the surface.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] Engineering the antifouling agents and the ablation rate can produce long-lived protection from the deleterious effects of biofouling.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] Firestopping and fireproofing products can be ablative in nature.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] This can mean endothermic materials, or merely materials that are sacrificial and become "spent" over time while exposed to fire, such as silicone firestop products.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] Given sufficient time under fire or heat conditions, these products char away, crumble, and disappear.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] The idea is to put enough of this material in the way of the fire that a level of fire-resistance rating can be maintained, as demonstrated in a fire test.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] Ablative materials usually have a large concentration of organic matter that is reduced by fire to ashes.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] In the case of silicone, organic rubber surrounds very finely divided silica dust (up to 380 m2 of combined surface area of all the dust particles per gram of this dust).
[src:ablative-case/ablation] When the organic rubber is exposed to fire, it burns to ash and leaves behind the silica dust with which the product started.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] Protoplanetary disks are rotating circumstellar disks of dense gas and dust surrounding young, newly formed stars.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] Shortly after star formation, stars often have leftover surrounding material that is still gravitationally bound to them, forming primitive disks that orbit around the star's equator – not too dissimilarly from the rings of Saturn.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] This occurs because the decrease in the protostellar material's radius during formation increases angular momentum, which means that this remaining material gets whipped into a flattened circumstellar disk around the star.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] This circumstellar disk may eventually mature into what is referred to as a protoplanetary disk: a disk of gas, dust, ice and other materials from which planetary systems may form.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] In these disks, orbiting matter starts to accrete in the colder mid-plane of the disk from dust grains and ices sticking together.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] These small accretions grow from pebbles to rocks to early baby planets, called planetesimals, then protoplanets, and eventually, full planets.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] As it is believed that massive stars may play a role in actively triggering star formation (by introducing gravitational instabilities amongst other factors), it is plausible that young, smaller stars with disks may be living relatively nearby to older, more massive stars.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] This has already been confirmed through observations to be the case in certain clusters, e.g. in the Trapezium cluster.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] Since massive stars tend to collapse through supernovae at the end of their lives, research is now investigating what role the shockwave of such an explosion, and the resulting supernova remnant (SNR), would play if it occurred in the line of fire of a protoplanetary disk.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] According to computationally modelled simulations, a SNR striking a protoplanetary disk would result in significant ablation of the disk, and this ablation would strip a significant amount of protoplanetary material from the disk – but not necessarily destroy the disk entirely.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] This is an important point because a disk that survives such an interaction with sufficient material leftover to form a planetary system may inherit an altered disk chemistry from the SNR, which could have effects on the planetary systems that later form.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] In spacecraft design, ablation is used to both cool and protect mechanical parts and/or payloads that would otherwise be damaged by extremely high temperatures.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] Two principal applications are heat shields for spacecraft entering a planetary atmosphere from space and cooling of rocket engine nozzles.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] Examples include the Apollo Command Module that protected astronauts from the heat of atmospheric reentry and the Kestrel second stage rocket engine designed for exclusive use in an environment of space vacuum since no heat convection is possible.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] In a basic sense, ablative material is designed so that instead of heat being transmitted into the structure of the spacecraft, only the outer surface of the material bears the majority of the heating effect.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] The outer surface chars and burns away – but quite slowly, only gradually exposing new fresh protective material beneath.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] The heat is carried away from the spacecraft by the gases generated by the ablative process, and never penetrates the surface material, so the metallic and other sensitive structures they protect, remain at a safe temperature.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] As the surface burns and disperses into space, the remaining solid material continues to insulate the craft from ongoing heat and superheated gases.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] The thickness of the ablative layer is calculated to be sufficient to survive the heat it will encounter on its mission.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] There is an entire branch of spaceflight research involving the search for new fireproofing materials to achieve the best ablative performance; this function is critical to protect the spacecraft occupants and payload from otherwise excessive heat loading.
[src:ablative-case/ablation] The same technology is used in some passive fire protection applications, in some cases by the same vendors, who offer different versions of these fireproofing products, some for aerospace and some for structural fire protection.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-armor] Ablative hull armor appears in the *Star Trek* universe.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-armor] Having been introduced in the year 2371 of *Star Trek*'s fictional future timeline, it features on starships including the USS *Defiant*, USS *Prometheus*, and an upgraded USS *Voyager*.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-armor] The *Star Trek: Deep Space Nine Technical Manual* explains that ablative armor works in two stages: When the shields are hit by an energy or particle weapon, thermal energy from the ship is dissipated across the hull.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-armor] The boil-off rate creates a particle cloud that is dense enough to disperse the incoming beam's energy.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-armor] In the online game *DarkSpace*, ablative armor is utilized to counter projectile-based damage while making the ship more vulnerable to lasers and energy-based weapons.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-armor] In the Universal Century time line of the *Gundam* series, ablative coatings are used to minimize the effect of beam weapons, called beam resistive coating and a later improved version, Anti-beam coating.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-armor] In the Cosmic Era time line, the ablative armor concept is applied in similar capacity to the anti-beam coating and laminated armor technologies utilised by mobile suits as a form of protection against beam and laser weaponry.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-armor] Selected spacecraft are also able to deploy ablative gel for high-velocity atmospheric reentries.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-armor] In the Anno Domini time line, the Earth's three space elevators are covered by ablative armor plates to protect their structures from damage.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-armor] When one of the elevators is partially destroyed, purging these plates require the technical crew to jettison the counterweight at the orbital end in order to avoid the now-unbalanced elevator's complete collapse.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-armor] In the online game *EVE Online*, ablative armor plating is utilized as a secondary defensive layer that protects the relatively fragile internal systems.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-armor] Depending on the ship's loadout configuration, a ship can continuously repair incoming damage on the armor, fit additional armor plates to sustain large amounts of damage in the short term, or remotely repair friendly ships' armor using specialized modules.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-armor] The rate at which the armor gets depleted depends on the types of damage incurred to the armor and the armor's resistance value against each particular type of damage.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-armor] Armor plating is usually considered strong against electromagnetic and thermal damage, and weak against kinetic energy penetrators and bombardment of subatomic particles (explosive), although a few exceptions exist.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-armor] In the console and PC game *Mass Effect* there are several variants of armor for all species referred to as ablative.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-armor] In the tabletop RPG Inquisitor, ablative armor may be layered on top of other armor.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-armor] If the ablative armor is struck, it is destroyed (after the damage caused by the attack is reduced accordingly).
[src:ablative-case/ablative-armor] Ablative armor may have additional properties such as added resistance to heat- or laser-based weaponry; if special ablative armor is destroyed, it loses those additional properties.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-armor] Unlike other types of armor in-game, ablative armor is quite cheap to purchase (since it is so easily destroyed).
[src:ablative-case/ablative-armor] In the tabletop wargame some armored vehicles, like the Astra Militarum's Sentinel walker, have ablative plating to help reduce damage to the pilot and survive the high power weaponry often faced in the game's setting.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-armor] In *Battle Pirates*, ablative armor is used to increase resistance to explosive damage on a ship.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-armor] In the table top role playing game *Traveller*, ablative armor (referred to as Ablat) is an equipment option for characters to protect them from laser fire or other energy weapons.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-armor] In the second edition of *Traveller* published by Game Designers's Workshop in 1981, Ablat is described as an "Ablative (vaporizing anti-laser) jacket" available for 75 credits on Tech Level 9+ worlds.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-armor] The 2016 Mongoose *Traveller Central Supply Catalog* also includes Ablat with the same cost and technology requirement.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-case] In grammar, the **ablative case** (pronounced /ˈæblətɪv/ *AB-lə-tiv*; abbreviated **abl**) is a grammatical case for nouns, pronouns, and adjectives in the grammars of various languages.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-case] It is used to indicate motion away from something.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-case] In different languages it can additionally serve various other purposes, *e.g.*, to make comparisons (in Armenian).
[src:ablative-case/ablative-case] The word "ablative" derives from the Latin *ablatus*, the (suppletive) perfect, passive participle of *auferre* "to carry away".
[src:ablative-case/ablative-case] The ablative case is found in several language families, such as Indo-European (e.g.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-case] Sanskrit, Latin, Albanian, Armenian, Punjabi), Turkic (e.g.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-case] Turkish, Turkmen, Azerbaijani, Uzbek, Kazakh, Kyrgyz, Tatar), Tungusic (e.g.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-case] Hungarian), and the Dravidian languages.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-case] There is no ablative case in modern Germanic languages such as German and English.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-case] There was an ablative case in the early stages of Ancient Greek, but it quickly fell into disuse by the classical period.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-case] The ablative case in Latin (*cāsus ablātīvus*) appears in various grammatical constructions, including following various prepositions, in an ablative absolute clause, and adverbially.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-case] The Latin ablative case was derived from three Proto-Indo-European cases: ablative (from), instrumental (with), and locative (in/at).
[src:ablative-case/ablative-case] In Ancient Greek, there was an ablative case (ἀφαιρετικὴ πτῶσις *aphairetikē ptōsis*) which was used in the Homeric, pre-Mycenaean, and Mycenean periods.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-case] It fell into disuse during the classical period and thereafter with some of its functions taken by the genitive and others by the dative.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-case] The genitive case with the prepositions ἀπό *apó* 'away from' and ἐκ/ἐξ *ek/ex* 'out of' is an example.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-case] German does not have an ablative case but, exceptionally, Latin ablative case-forms were used from the seventeenth to the nineteenth century after some prepositions, for example after *von* in *von dem Nomine*: ablative of the Latin loanword *nomen*.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-case] Grammarians at that time, Justus Georg Schottel, Kaspar von Stieler, Johann Balthasar von Antesperg and Johann Christoph Gottsched, listed an ablative case (as the sixth case after nominative, genitive, dative, accusative and vocative) for German words.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-case] They considered the dative case after some prepositions to be an ablative, as in *von dem Mann[e]* 'from the man, of the man' and *mit dem Mann[e]* 'with the man', while they considered the dative case after other prepositions or without a preposition, as in *dem Mann[e]*, to be a dative.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-case] The ablative case is found in Albanian; it is the fifth case, *rasa rrjedhore*.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-case] In Sanskrit, the ablative case is the fifth case (*pañcamī*) and has a similar function to that in Latin.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-case] Sanskrit nouns in the ablative often refer to a subject "out of" which or "from" whom something (an action, an object) has arisen or occurred: *pátram **vṛkṣā́t** pátati* 'the leaf falls **from the tree**'.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-case] It is also used for nouns in several other senses, as for actions occurring "because of" or "without" a certain noun, indicating distance or direction.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-case] When it appears with a comparative adjective, (*śreṣṭhatamam* 'the best'), the ablative is used to refer to what the adjective is comparing: 'better than X'.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-case] The modern Armenian ablative has different markers for each main dialect, both originating from Classical Armenian.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-case] The Western Armenian affix -է *-ē* (definite -էն *-ēn*) derives from the classical singular; the Eastern Armenian affix -ից *-ic’* (both indefinite and definite) derives from the classical plural.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-case] For both dialects, those affixes are singular, with the corresponding plurals being -(ն)երէ(ն) *-(n)erē(n)* and -(ն)երից *-(n)eric’*.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-case] In Finnish, the ablative case is the sixth of the locative cases with the meaning "from, off, of": *pöytä – pöydältä* "table – off from the table".
[src:ablative-case/ablative-case] It is an outer locative case, used like the adessive and allative cases, to denote both being on top of something and "being around the place" (as opposed to the inner locative case, the elative, which means "from out of" or "from the inside of").
[src:ablative-case/ablative-case] With the locative, the receding object was near the other place or object, not inside it.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-case] The Finnish ablative is also used in time expressions to indicate times of something happening (*kymmeneltä* "at ten") as well as with verbs expressing feelings or emotions.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-case] The Finnish ablative has the ending *-lta* or *-ltä*, depending on vowel harmony.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-case] The ablative case in Estonian is the ninth case and has a similar function to that in Hungarian.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-case] The ablative case in Hungarian is used to describe movement away from, as well as a concept, object, act or event originating from an object, person, location or entity.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-case] When used to describe movement away from a location, the case may only refer to movement from *the general vicinity* of the location and not from inside of it.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-case] Thus, *a postától jövök* would mean one had been standing *next to* the post office before, not inside the building.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-case] When the case is used to refer to the origin of a possible act or event, the act/event may be implied while not explicitly stated, such as *Meg foglak védeni a rabló**tól***: I will defend you from the robber.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-case] The application of vowel harmony gives two different suffixes: *-tól* and *-től*.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-case] These are applied to back-vowel and front-vowel words, respectively.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-case] Hungarian has a narrower delative case, similar to ablative, but more specific: movement off/from a surface of something, with suffixes *-ról* and *-ről*.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-case] In some situations simple ablative can have a "because of" meaning; in these situations, ablative can be optionally followed by the postposition *dolayı* 'because of'.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-case] The ablative in Manchu is expressed through the suffix *-ci* and can also be used to express comparisons.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-case] It is usually not directly attached to its parent word.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-case] The ablative in Evenki is expressed with the suffix *-duk*.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-latin] In Latin grammar, the **ablative case** (*cāsus ablātīvus*) is one of the six noun cases.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-latin] Traditionally, it is the sixth case (*cāsus sextus, cāsus latīnus*).
[src:ablative-case/ablative-latin] It has forms and functions derived from the Proto-Indo-European ablative, instrumental, and locative.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-latin] It expresses concepts similar to those of the English prepositions *from*; *with*, *by*; and *in*, *at*.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-latin] It is sometimes called the adverbial case, since phrases in the ablative can be translated as adverbs: *incrēdibilī celeritāte*, 'with incredible speed', or 'very quickly'.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-latin] Some uses of the ablative descend from the Proto-Indo-European ablative case.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-latin] It can also be used for the whole to which a certain number belongs or is a part.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-latin] Some uses of the ablative descend from the Proto-Indo-European instrumental case.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-latin] Some meanings of the ablative descend from the Proto-Indo-European locative case.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-latin] The ablative case is very frequently used with prepositions, for example *ex urbe* "out of the city", *cum eō* "with him".
[src:ablative-case/ablative-latin] Four prepositions (*in* "in/into", *sub* "under/to the foot of", *subter* "under", *super* "over") may take either an accusative or an ablative.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-latin] In the case of the first two, the accusative indicates motion, and the ablative indicates no motion.
[src:ablative-case/ablative-latin] For instance, *in urbe* means "in the city"; *in urbem*, "into the city".
[src:ablative-case/ablative-latin] In the case of *super*, the accusative means "above" or "over", and the ablative means "concerning".
[src:ablative-case/absolutive-case] In grammar, the **absolutive case** (abbreviated **abs**) is the case of nouns in ergative–absolutive languages that would generally be the subjects of intransitive verbs or the objects of transitive verbs in the translational equivalents of nominative–accusative languages such as English.
[src:ablative-case/absolutive-case] In languages with ergative–absolutive alignment, the absolutive is the case used to mark both the subject of an intransitive verb and the object of a transitive verb in addition to being used for the citation form of a noun.
[src:ablative-case/absolutive-case] It contrasts with the marked ergative case, which marks the subject of a transitive verb.
[src:ablative-case/absolutive-case] In a very few cases, a marked absolutive has been reported, including in Nias and Sochiapam Chinantec.
[src:ablative-case/absolutive-case] Occasionally, the term 'absolutive case' (or also: 'absolute case') is used for the unmarked case form in languages with other alignment types.
[src:ablative-case/absolutive-case] This is especially common in the tradition of descriptive linguistics of African languages.
[src:ablative-case/absolutive-case] In marked nominative languages, where the nominative has case inflection, the accusative is unmarked and also serves as citation form.
[src:ablative-case/absolutive-case] In these languages, the unmarked accusative/citation form is thus often called 'absolutive'.
[src:ablative-case/absolutive-case] On the other hand, in certain nominative–accusative languages, it is the accusative which is explicitly marked for case, whereas the nominative is unmarked and serves as citation form.
[src:ablative-case/absolutive-case] In such situations, the term 'absolutive' is occasionally used to describe the unmarked nominative/citation form.
[src:ablative-case/absolutive-case] In tripartite languages, both the agent and object of a transitive clause have case forms, ergative and accusative, and the agent of an intransitive clause is the unmarked citation form.
[src:ablative-case/absolutive-case] It is occasionally called the intransitive case, but *absolutive* is also used and is perhaps more accurate since it is not limited to core agents of intransitive verbs.
[src:ablative-case/accusative-case] In grammar, the **accusative case** (abbreviated **acc**) of a noun is the grammatical case used to receive the direct object of a transitive verb.
[src:ablative-case/accusative-case] In the English language, the only words that occur in the accusative case are pronouns: "me", "him", "her", "us", "whom", and "them".
[src:ablative-case/accusative-case] For example, the pronoun *she*, as the subject of a clause, is in the nominative case ("She wrote a book"); but if the pronoun is instead the object of the verb, it is in the accusative case and *she* becomes *her* ("Fred greeted her").
[src:ablative-case/accusative-case] For compound direct objects, it would be, e.g., "Fred invited me and her to the party".
[src:ablative-case/accusative-case] The accusative case is used in many languages for the objects of (some or all) prepositions.
[src:ablative-case/accusative-case] It is usually combined with the nominative case (for example in Latin).
[src:ablative-case/accusative-case] The English term, "accusative", derives from the Latin *accusativus*, which, in turn, is a translation of the Greek αἰτιατική.
[src:ablative-case/accusative-case] The word can also mean "causative", and that might have derived from the Greeks, but the sense of the Roman translation has endured and is used in some other modern languages as the grammatical term for this case, for example in Russian (винительный).
[src:ablative-case/accusative-case] Some Balto-Finnic languages, such as Finnish, have two cases for objects, the accusative and the partitive case.
[src:ablative-case/accusative-case] In morphosyntactic alignment terms, both do the accusative function, but the accusative object is telic, while the partitive is not.
[src:ablative-case/accusative-case] Modern English almost entirely lacks declension in its nouns; pronouns, however, have an understood case usage, as in *them*, *her*, *him* and *whom*, which merges the accusative and dative functions, and originates in old Germanic dative forms (see Declension in English).
[src:ablative-case/accusative-case] In the sentence *The man sees **the dog***, *the dog* is the direct object of the verb "to see".
[src:ablative-case/accusative-case] In English, which has mostly lost grammatical cases, the definite article and noun – "the dog" – remain the same noun form without number agreement in the noun either as subject or object, though an artifact of it is in the verb and has number agreement, which changes to "sees".
[src:ablative-case/accusative-case] In a declined language, the morphology of the article or noun changes with gender agreement.
[src:ablative-case/accusative-case] For example, in German, "the dog" is *der Hund*.
[src:ablative-case/accusative-case] This is the form in the nominative case, used for the subject of a sentence.
[src:ablative-case/accusative-case] If this article/noun pair is used as the object of a verb, it (usually) changes to the accusative case, which entails an article shift in German – *Der Mann sieht **den Hund*** (The man sees the dog).
[src:ablative-case/accusative-case] In German, masculine nouns change their definite article from *der* to *den* in the accusative case.
[src:ablative-case/accusative-case] In Nepali, "Rama sees Shyama" would be translated as रामले श्यामलाई देख्छ। *Rama-le Shyama-lai dekhchha.* The same sentence in Sanskrit would be रामः पश्यति श्यामम्। *Rama: pashyati Shyamam*.
[src:ablative-case/accusative-case] The accusative case in Latin has minor differences from the accusative case in Proto-Indo-European.
[src:ablative-case/accusative-case] For the accusative endings, see Latin declensions.
[src:ablative-case/accusative-case] The accusative case is used for the direct object in a sentence.
[src:ablative-case/accusative-case] The masculine forms for German articles, e.g., "the", "a/an", "my", etc., change in the accusative case: they always end in -en.
[src:ablative-case/accusative-case] The feminine, neutral and plural forms do not change.
[src:ablative-case/accusative-case] Some German pronouns also change in the accusative case.
[src:ablative-case/accusative-case] The accusative case is also used after particular German prepositions.
[src:ablative-case/accusative-case] These include *bis*, *durch*, *für*, *gegen*, *ohne*, *um*, after which the accusative case is always used, and *an*, *auf*, *hinter*, *in*, *neben*, *über*, *unter*, *vor*, *zwischen* which can govern either the accusative or the dative.
[src:ablative-case/accusative-case] The latter prepositions take the accusative when motion or action is specified (being done into/onto the space), but take the dative when location is specified (being done in/on that space).
[src:ablative-case/accusative-case] These prepositions are also used in conjunction with certain verbs, in which case it is the verb in question which governs whether the accusative or dative should be used.
[src:ablative-case/accusative-case] Adjective endings also change in the accusative case.
[src:ablative-case/accusative-case] Another factor that determines the endings of adjectives is whether the adjective is being used after a definite article (the), after an indefinite article (a/an) or without any article before the adjective (*many* green apples).
[src:ablative-case/accusative-case] In German, the accusative case is also used for some adverbial expressions, mostly temporal ones, as in *Diesen Abend bleibe ich daheim* (This evening I'm staying at home), where *diesen Abend* is marked as accusative, although not a direct object.
[src:ablative-case/accusative-case] In Russian, accusative is used not only to display the direct object of an action, but also to indicate the destination or goal of motion.
[src:ablative-case/accusative-case] The prepositions в and на can both take accusative in situations where they are indicating the goal of a motion.
[src:ablative-case/accusative-case] In the masculine, Russian also distinguishes between animate and inanimate nouns with regard to the accusative; only the animates carry a marker in this case.
[src:ablative-case/accusative-case] The PIE accusative case has nearly eroded in Russian, merging with the genitive or the nominative in most declensions.
[src:ablative-case/accusative-case] Only singular first-declension nouns (ending in 'а', 'я', or 'ия') have a distinct accusative ('у', 'ю', or 'ию').
[src:ablative-case/accusative-case] In Polish, the accusative case has two functions: showing the direct object of an action, and showing the goal of motion.
[src:ablative-case/accusative-case] Inanimate masculine nouns in accusative case are usually written the same as in nominative case, whereas animate masculine nouns receive the ending ***-a***.
[src:ablative-case/accusative-case] Feminine nouns ending with a consonant are written the same as in nominative case.
[src:ablative-case/accusative-case] Neuter nouns are written the same in accusative case as they are in nominative case.
[src:ablative-case/accusative-case] The direct object function of the accusative case in Polish is often used with verbs like *mieć* 'to have', *jeść* 'to eat', *pić* 'to drink', *czytać* 'to read' and *lubić* 'to like'.
[src:ablative-case/accusative-case] The motion function of the accusative case is used with the prepositions *na*, *o*, *po*, *pod*, *przez(e)*, *w(e)*, and *za*.
[src:ablative-case/accusative-case] According to the traditional Finnish grammar, the accusative case is used for a total object, while the partitive case is used for a partial object.
[src:ablative-case/accusative-case] The accusative is identical to either the nominative case or the genitive case, except for personal pronouns and the personal interrogative pronoun *kuka*/*ken*, which have a special accusative form ending in *-t*.
[src:ablative-case/accusative-case] The major new Finnish grammar, *Iso suomen kielioppi*, deviates from the traditional classification to limit the accusative case to the special case of personal pronouns and *kuka*/*ken*.
[src:ablative-case/accusative-case] This grammar considers other total objects as being in the nominative or genitive case.
[src:ablative-case/accusative-case] The accusative case is assigned to the direct object in a sentence in Hungarian.
[src:ablative-case/accusative-case] The accusative marker is always *-t*, often preceded by a linking vowel to facilitate pronunciation.
[src:ablative-case/accusative-case] Every personal pronoun has an accusative form.
[src:ablative-case/accusative-case] For the Hungarian 1st and 2nd person singular accusative forms, the pronoun can often be dropped if it is clear from the context who the speaker is referring to.
[src:ablative-case/accusative-case] Accusative case marking existed in Proto-Semitic, Akkadian, and Ugaritic.
[src:ablative-case/accusative-case] It is preserved today in many Semitic languages as Modern Standard Arabic, Hebrew and Ge'ez.
[src:ablative-case/accusative-case] The accusative case is called in Arabic النصب (*an-naṣb*) and it has many other uses in addition to marking the object of a verb.
[src:ablative-case/accusative-case] In Hebrew, if the object of the sentence is a pronoun (e.g., I, you, s/he) and the transitive verb requires a direct object, the word אֵת *et* is combined with the pronoun into an object pronoun.
[src:ablative-case/accusative-case] In Japanese, cases are marked by placing particles after nouns.
[src:ablative-case/accusative-case] The accusative case is marked with を (*wo*, pronounced /o̞/).
[src:ablative-case/accusative-case] In Korean, the accusative case is marked with 를 or 을.
[src:ablative-case/accusative-case] The postpositions depend on a word's last syllable.
[src:ablative-case/accusative-case] In Turkish, cases are marked with suffixes.
[src:ablative-case/accusative-case] The accusative case is marked with the suffixes *-ı, -i, -u, -ü*, depending on vowel harmony.
[src:ablative-case/accusative-case] If a word ends in a vowel, *-y-* is added before the suffix as a buffer consonant.
[src:ablative-case/accusative-case] The accusative is only used if the direct object of a sentence is definite.
[src:ablative-case/accusative-case] If it is indefinite, the nominative case is used.
[src:ablative-case/accusative-case] In Malayalam, the accusative inflection is achieved using the suffix എ /-e/.
[src:ablative-case/accusative-case] The sandhi also play a role here depending on the ending of the noun.
[src:ablative-case/accusative-case] Example: മരം /maram/ → മരത്തെ /maratte/ where /tt/ replaces /m/ when /e/ is suffixed.
[src:ablative-case/adessive] An **adessive case** (abbreviated **ade**; from Latin *adesse* "to be present (at)": *ad* "at" + *esse* "to be") is a grammatical case generally denoting location at, upon, or adjacent to the referent of the noun; the term is used most frequently for Uralic studies.
[src:ablative-case/adessive] For Uralic languages, such as Finnish, Estonian and Hungarian, it is the fourth of the locative cases, with the basic meaning of "on"—for example, Estonian **laud** (table) and **laual** (on the table), Hungarian **asztal** and **asztalnál** (at the table).
[src:ablative-case/adessive] It is also used as an instrumental case in Finnish.
[src:ablative-case/adessive] For Finnish, the suffix is **-lla*/*-llä**, e.g.
[src:ablative-case/adessive] **pöytä** (table) and **pöydällä** (on the table).
[src:ablative-case/adessive] In addition, it can specify "being around the place", as in **koululla** (at the school including the schoolyard), as contrasted with the inessive **koulussa** (in the school, inside the building).
[src:ablative-case/adessive] In Estonian, the ending *-l* is added to the genitive case, e.g.
[src:ablative-case/adessive] Besides the meaning "on", this case is also used to indicate ownership.
[src:ablative-case/adessive] For example, "mehel on auto" means "the man owns a car".
[src:ablative-case/adessive] As the Uralic languages don't possess the verb "to have", the concept is expressed as a subject in the adessive case + *on* (for example, **minulla on**, "I have", literally "at me is").
[src:ablative-case/adessive] The Finnish adessive case has the word ending *-lla* or *-llä* (according to the rules of vowel harmony).
[src:ablative-case/adessive] It is usually added to nouns and associated adjectives.
[src:ablative-case/adessive] though they are not strictly a use of the adessive case).
[src:ablative-case/adessive] Other languages which employ an adessive case or case function include archaic varieties of Lithuanian (which likely developed by the influence of Uralic), some Northeast Caucasian languages such as Lezgian and Hunzib, and the Ossetic languages, both ancient and modern.
